Abstract

This dissertation establishes the mathematical foundations and architectural design of the Neuromorphic Somatic‑Meta Architecture (NSMA) , a formal framework for embodied safety in autonomous systems. The framework is instantiated in a theoretical case study: the E4 TECH‑SUPPORT autonomous intervention platform.

Core Contribution: A mathematically rigorous architecture that integrates embodiment, perception, and cognition into a single safety‑aware structure via:

· Somatic Safety Manifolds – a differential‑geometric model of the robot’s body with a safety‑aware Riemannian metric;
· Sheaf‑Theoretic Sensor Fusion – an information‑geometric model of distributed sensing with cohomological inconsistency detection;
· Somatic Control Barrier Functions – a generalization of CBFs that incorporates sensor states;
· Homotopy‑Type Safety Certificates – a category‑theoretic framework for certificate equivalence and modular composition, formulated in homotopy type theory with the univalence axiom.

Critical Scope: This document is a purely theoretical specification. All components are defined mathematically; no implementation, simulation, or experimental validation is proposed or required. Safety claims are expressed as theorems about the mathematical model, not about any physical realization.

