1. Mathematical Foundations of NSMA

1.1 Body Manifold with Safety‑Aware Riemannian Metric

The physical embodiment of an autonomous agent is modelled as a smooth manifold that incorporates both rigid and deformable structures, as well as safety‑critical constraints.

Definition 1.1 (Body Manifold).
Let B be a smooth manifold of dimension n representing all possible configurations of the agent’s body. For the E4 platform, which consists of 28 rigid links, flexible elements, and tool attachments, we set

\mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}} = \left(\prod_{i=1}^{28} SE(3)_i\right) \times \mathbb{R}^{m}_{\text{flex}} \times \mathbb{R}^{k}_{\text{tool}},

where each SE(3)_i is the Lie group of rigid displacements for link i, \mathbb{R}^{m}_{\text{flex}} parameterises continuum‑deformable elements, and \mathbb{R}^{k}_{\text{tool}} captures tool‑frame offsets. The manifold \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}} is assumed to be Hausdorff and second‑countable, hence paracompact.

To encode safety, we equip \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}} with a Riemannian metric that penalises motions approaching unsafe regions.

Definition 1.2 (Safety‑Aware Riemannian Metric).
Let M(q) be the mass‑inertia matrix, a smooth section of \operatorname{Sym}^2_+(T^*\mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}) (positive definite). Let \mathcal{D}, \mathcal{H}: T\mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}} \times T\mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}} \to \mathbb{R} be smooth symmetric bilinear forms that are positive semi‑definite for each q. For constants \lambda_{\text{damage}}, \lambda_{\text{human}} \ge 0, define

g_S(q)(v,w) = v^\top M(q) w + \lambda_{\text{damage}} \cdot \mathcal{D}(q,v,w) + \lambda_{\text{human}} \cdot \mathcal{H}(q,v,w).

Lemma 1.3 (Metric Validity).
For every q \in \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}, g_S(q) is a positive definite inner product on T_q\mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}. Consequently, g_S is a Riemannian metric on \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}.

Proof. M(q) is positive definite by definition, while \mathcal{D} and \mathcal{H} are positive semi‑definite. For any non‑zero v, g_S(q)(v,v) \ge v^\top M(q) v > 0. Symmetry and bilinearity follow from those of the summands. Smoothness holds because each term is smooth.

Definition 1.4 (Safety Margin).
Let \partial U \subset \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}} be a closed subset representing unsafe configurations (e.g., joint limits, self‑collision boundaries, human proximity zones). The geodesic distance induced by g_S provides a differentiable safety margin:

d_{\text{safe}}(q) = \inf_{q' \in \partial U} \inf \left\{ \int_0^1 \sqrt{g_S(\dot\gamma(t),\dot\gamma(t))}\,dt \;\middle|\; \gamma(0)=q,\ \gamma(1)=q',\ \gamma \text{ piecewise smooth} \right\}.

1.2 Sensor Statistical Manifolds

Each sensor type produces readings that depend on the true physical state. We model this by associating to each sensor a statistical manifold.

Definition 1.5 (Sensor Statistical Manifold).
For sensor type i, let \Theta_i \subseteq \mathbb{R}^{d_i} be an open set of parameters (e.g., true force, orientation). For each \theta \in \Theta_i, let p_i(\cdot|\theta) be a probability density function on a measurable space \mathcal{X}_i. The family

\mathcal{S}_i = \{ p_i(\cdot|\theta) \mid \theta \in \Theta_i \}

is a statistical manifold, assumed to be a smooth manifold with atlas given by the parameterisation \theta \mapsto p_i(\cdot|\theta). The Fisher–Rao metric on \mathcal{S}_i is the Riemannian metric defined for tangent vectors u,v \in T_\theta \mathcal{S}_i \cong \mathbb{R}^{d_i} by

g_{FR}^{(i)}(\theta)(u,v) = \mathbb{E}_{x \sim p_i(\cdot|\theta)}\left[ \frac{\partial \log p_i}{\partial \theta}(x;\theta)\, u \;\cdot\; \frac{\partial \log p_i}{\partial \theta}(x;\theta)\, v \right].

1.3 Sheaf‑Theoretic Sensor Fusion

We model the distributed sensor system using a sheaf over the nerve of an open cover of the body manifold.

Definition 1.6 (Sensor Cover).
Let \mathcal{U} = \{U_\alpha\}_{\alpha \in A} be a locally finite open cover of \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}} such that each U_\alpha is the region monitored by a fixed subset of sensors. For each \alpha, let I_\alpha \subset \{1,\dots,N\} be the indices of sensors covering U_\alpha.

Definition 1.7 (Sheaf of Sensor Sections).
For each open set U \subseteq \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}, define \mathcal{F}(U) to be the set of tuples (s_i)_{i \in I} where I is the set of sensors covering U and each s_i: U \to \mathcal{S}_i is a smooth section of the statistical manifold bundle (viewed as a trivial bundle U \times \mathcal{S}_i). Restriction maps are given by restricting each section and projecting to the sensors that remain. This defines a presheaf on the category of open subsets of \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}. By construction, it satisfies the sheaf axioms (locality and gluing) because the conditions are local and sections can be patched uniquely when they agree on overlaps.

Definition 1.8 (Čech Nerve and Cohomology).
Let N(\mathcal{U}) be the nerve of the cover, a simplicial complex whose vertices are the indices \alpha and where a k-simplex \sigma = \{\alpha_0,\dots,\alpha_k\} appears iff U_{\alpha_0} \cap \cdots \cap U_{\alpha_k} \neq \emptyset. For each k \ge 0, define the Čech cochain group

C^k(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{F}) = \prod_{\sigma \in N(\mathcal{U})_k} \mathcal{F}(U_\sigma),

where U_\sigma = U_{\alpha_0} \cap \cdots \cap U_{\alpha_k}. The Čech coboundary operator \delta^k: C^k \to C^{k+1} is given by the usual alternating sum of restrictions. A global section of \mathcal{F} corresponds to a 0‑cochain \hat{s} \in C^0 that is a cocycle: \delta^0 \hat{s} = 0. The obstruction to global consistency lies in H^1(\mathcal{U}, \mathcal{F}) = \ker \delta^1 / \operatorname{im} \delta^0.

Definition 1.9 (Inconsistency Measure).
Given a 0‑cochain \hat{s} representing local estimates, define its inconsistency norm as

\|\delta^0 \hat{s}\| = \sqrt{ \sum_{\alpha,\beta} \int_{U_\alpha \cap U_\beta} \| \hat{s}_\alpha - \hat{s}_\beta \|^2_{g_{FR}} \, dV_{g_S} },

where the integrand uses the Fisher–Rao metric on the fibre. If this norm is zero, \hat{s} glues to a global section; otherwise, its cohomology class [\delta^0 \hat{s}] indicates the nature and location of inconsistency.

1.4 Somatic Safety Manifold

The somatic safety manifold unifies body and sensor states into a single geometric object.

Definition 1.10 (Somatic Safety Manifold).
Let

\mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}} = \bigsqcup_{q \in \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}} \prod_{i=1}^N \mathcal{S}_i,

with the smooth structure induced by the product of the base manifold and the fibre manifolds. The projection \pi: \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}} \to \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}} given by \pi(q,(s_i)) = q is a smooth submersion. Local trivialisations exist because each \mathcal{S}_i is a smooth manifold and the product is locally trivial; thus \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}} is a fibre bundle over \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}} with fibre F = \prod_i \mathcal{S}_i. Transition functions are induced by changes of local coordinates on the base and the natural identifications of the fibres.

Definition 1.11 (Safety Section).
A safety section is a smooth map s_{\text{safe}}: \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}} \to \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}} such that \pi \circ s_{\text{safe}} = \operatorname{id}_{\mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}}. It represents the expected sensor distribution in a nominal safe state. The somatic potential V: \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}} \to \mathbb{R} measures the deviation from the safety section; for example,

V(q,\sigma) = \| \sigma - s_{\text{safe}}(q) \|^2_{g_{FR}}.

Definition 1.12 (Reflex Gradient Flow).
Equip \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}} with a bundle metric g_{\text{reflex}} that respects the fibre metric and the base metric (e.g., a Sasaki‑type metric). The reflex dynamics are given by the negative gradient flow of V with respect to this metric:

\frac{d}{dt} x = - \operatorname{grad}_{g_{\text{reflex}}} V(x), \qquad x = (q,\sigma) \in \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}}.

This provides a geometric analogue of low‑level pain reflexes, driving the system back toward the safety section.

1.5 Somatic Control Barrier Functions

Control Barrier Functions (CBFs) are extended to incorporate somatic states, providing safety guarantees for the coupled body‑sensor system.

Definition 1.13 (Somatic Control System).
Consider control affine dynamics on the somatic manifold:

\dot x = f(x) + g(x) u, \qquad x = (q,\sigma) \in \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}}, \ u \in \mathcal{U} \subseteq \mathbb{R}^m,

where f and g are smooth vector fields and \mathcal{U} is a compact convex set. The sensor dynamics are included in f; i.e., f(x) = (f_{\text{body}}(q,\sigma), f_{\text{sensor}}(q,\sigma)) with f_{\text{sensor}} derived from the sensor models.

Definition 1.14 (Somatic Control Barrier Function).
A differentiable function h: \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}} \to \mathbb{R} is a somatic control barrier function (SCBF) if there exists an extended class‑\mathcal{K}_\infty function \alpha such that for all x,

\sup_{u \in \mathcal{U}} \left[ L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) u + \frac{\partial h}{\partial \sigma} f_{\text{sensor}}(x) \right] \ge - \alpha(h(x)).

Here L_f h and L_g h are Lie derivatives with respect to the body dynamics only; the term \frac{\partial h}{\partial \sigma} f_{\text{sensor}} accounts for sensor evolution.

Assumption 1.15 (SCBF Existence Conditions).
A sufficient condition for the existence of an SCBF on a compact safe set \mathcal{C} \subset \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}} is that:

1. The system has relative degree one with respect to h on \partial\mathcal{C} (i.e., L_g h(x) \neq 0 for x \in \partial\mathcal{C}).
2. The set \mathcal{C} is controlled invariant in the sense of viability theory.
3. There exists a Lipschitz continuous controller that renders \mathcal{C} forward invariant; then by converse barrier function theorems (e.g., [Jankovic 2018]), a smooth SCBF can be constructed.

In practice, h may be synthesised via sum‑of‑squares programming if the dynamics are polynomial.

Theorem 1.16 (Forward Invariance).
If h is an SCBF and x_0 \in \mathcal{C} = \{ x \mid h(x) \ge 0 \}, then any Lipschitz continuous controller k: \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}} \to \mathcal{U} satisfying

L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) k(x) + \frac{\partial h}{\partial \sigma} f_{\text{sensor}}(x) \ge - \alpha(h(x)) \quad \forall x

renders \mathcal{C} forward invariant: x(t) \in \mathcal{C} for all t \ge 0.

Proof. Along trajectories, \dot h \ge -\alpha(h); by the comparison lemma, h(t) \ge \beta(h_0,t) with \beta a class‑\mathcal{K}\mathcal{L} function, so h(t) \ge 0.

1.6 Homotopy‑Type Safety Certificates

Safety certificates are organised in a homotopy‑type theoretic framework to enable modular reasoning and certificate equivalence. We work within intensional Martin‑Löf type theory extended with the univalence axiom (Homotopy Type Theory / Univalent Foundations).

Definition 1.17 (Safety Certificate Type).
A safety certificate for a subsystem is a dependent record type:

\mathsf{Cert}(X, \phi, \pi) :\equiv \sum_{X : \mathcal{U}} \sum_{\phi : X \to \mathbb{R}} \pi : \mathsf{SCBF}(X,\phi),

where \mathsf{SCBF}(X,\phi) is the type of proofs that \phi satisfies the SCBF conditions on X (with appropriate dynamics). The type X is the state space, modelled as a smooth manifold; we assume a type of manifolds with a homotopy‑theoretic interpretation.

Definition 1.18 (Category \mathbf{SafeMon}).
Define a precategory \mathbf{SafeMon} whose:

· objects are terms of type \mathsf{Cert};
· morphisms from (X,\phi,\pi) to (Y,\psi,\rho) are smooth maps f: X \to Y together with a proof that \psi \circ f \ge \phi and that the SCBF conditions are preserved (i.e., the diagram of proofs commutes).

Composition is given by composition of smooth maps and concatenation of proofs.

Definition 1.19 (Universal Safety Monitor).
The Universal Safety Monitor is the functor U: \mathbf{SafeMon} \to \mathbf{Set} that sends a certificate to its underlying set of proofs (i.e., the type \pi) and sends a morphism to the induced map on proofs (pullback). It is representable if there exists a terminal object T such that U \cong \mathbf{SafeMon}(T, -). Indeed, the terminal object T = (\{*\}, \phi_T \equiv 1, \pi_T) exists because for any certificate, the constant map to \{*\} trivially preserves safety. Then U(C) \cong \mathbf{SafeMon}(T, C) holds naturally, so U is representable.

Definition 1.20 (Homotopy Equivalence of Certificates).
Two certificates C_1, C_2 are homotopy equivalent if there exist morphisms f: C_1 \to C_2 and g: C_2 \to C_1 such that g \circ f and f \circ g are homotopic to the respective identities (where homotopy is taken in the smooth category, i.e., smooth maps H: X_1 \times [0,1] \to X_1 with H(\cdot,0) = g\circ f and H(\cdot,1) = \operatorname{id}_{X_1}, and similarly for the other composition). By the univalence axiom, homotopy equivalence induces an identification C_1 = C_2 in the universe \mathcal{U}. Consequently, equivalent certificates can be substituted in any context, enabling seamless recomposition after verification.

