2. NSMA Layered Architecture

The NSMA architecture decomposes the autonomous system into five mathematically defined layers, each with formal interfaces.

2.1 Physical Layer

The physical layer is the smooth manifold \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}} equipped with the safety‑aware metric g_S and the dynamics vector field f_{\text{body}} (which may depend on control inputs). It models the robot’s kinematics, dynamics, and contact mechanics.

Interface P→S (Physical to Somatic).
A de Rham map \mathcal{I}: \Omega^k(\mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}) \to \Omega^k(\mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}}) lifts differential forms on the body to forms on the somatic bundle. In particular, the reflex potential V is obtained by integrating a 1‑form \omega_{\text{nociceptive}} that encodes unsafe contacts:

V(q,\sigma) = \int_\gamma \mathcal{I}(\omega_{\text{nociceptive}}),

where \gamma is a path in the bundle from a reference section to (q,\sigma).

2.2 Somatic Layer

The somatic layer fuses sensor readings into a coherent estimate of the somatic state. It uses the sheaf \mathcal{F} and the associated cohomology.

Definition 2.1 (Local Estimator).
For each open set U_\alpha, define a local estimator \hat{s}_\alpha \in \mathcal{F}(U_\alpha) as the maximum‑likelihood estimate based on the sensors covering U_\alpha. The collection \{\hat{s}_\alpha\} is a 0‑cochain.

Definition 2.2 (Consistency Check).
Compute \delta^0(\hat{s}); if it is zero, the \hat{s}_\alpha glue to a global section \hat{s} \in \mathcal{F}(\mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}). If non‑zero, the cohomology class [\delta^0(\hat{s})] \in H^1(N(\mathcal{U}), \mathcal{F}) identifies the obstruction, which may be used to trigger re‑calibration or fault handling.

Interface S→R (Somatic to Reactive).
The global section \hat{s} (or the obstruction class) is passed to the reactive layer as the current somatic state estimate x = (q,\hat{s}(q)).

2.3 Reactive Layer

The reactive layer implements low‑level safety‑critical control using SCBFs.

Definition 2.3 (SCBF Synthesis).
Given the dynamics on \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}} and a desired safe set \mathcal{C} = \{ x \mid h(x) \ge 0 \}, an SCBF is constructed by solving a feasibility problem. Under the assumptions of Definition 1.15, such an h exists. The reactive layer maintains a library of SCBFs for different operational modes.

Interface R→C (Reactive to Cognitive).
The reactive layer provides a safe action envelope

\mathcal{U}_{\text{safe}}(x) = \{ u \in \mathcal{U} \mid L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) u + \frac{\partial h}{\partial \sigma} f_{\text{sensor}}(x) \ge - \alpha(h(x)) \}

to the cognitive layer. Any control chosen from this envelope preserves safety.

2.4 Cognitive Layer

The cognitive layer plans high‑level actions while respecting the safe envelope. Plans are represented as dependent types, ensuring that safety constraints are satisfied by construction.

Definition 2.4 (Dependent Plan Type).
Let \mathsf{State} : \mathbb{N} \to \mathcal{U} be a family of types representing the state at discrete time steps (e.g.,  \mathsf{State}(t) = \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}}). A plan is a dependent function

P : \prod_{t:\mathbb{N}} \mathsf{State}(t) \to \mathsf{Action}(t),

where \mathsf{Action}(t) is the type of admissible controls at time t. A plan is safe if there exists a proof

\Pi : \prod_{t:\mathbb{N}} \prod_{s: \mathsf{State}(t)} \mathsf{In}(P(t,s), \mathcal{U}_{\text{safe}}(s)).

Definition 2.5 (Goal Achievement).
A plan achieves a goal G \subset \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}} if there exists a time T and a proof that the final state lies in G.

Interface C→M (Cognitive to Meta‑Safety).
The cognitive layer outputs a plan certificate: a term of type

\mathsf{CertPlan}(s_0, G) = \sum_{P:\mathsf{Plan}} \mathsf{Safe}(P) \times \mathsf{Achieves}(P, G),

where \mathsf{Safe}(P) and \mathsf{Achieves}(P, G) are proof types.

2.5 Meta‑Safety Layer

The meta‑safety layer verifies plan certificates and ensures that the overall system remains within the safety envelope, even under composition.

Definition 2.6 (Universal Safety Monitor Functor).
The Universal Safety Monitor is the functor U: \mathbf{SafeMon} \to \mathbf{Set} defined in Definition 1.19. Applied to a certificate C = (X,\phi,\pi), it returns the set of proofs \pi. For a plan certificate \mathsf{CertPlan}(s_0,G), we can view it as an object of \mathbf{SafeMon} by taking the state space to be the set of trajectories satisfying the plan; then U extracts the safety proof.

Definition 2.7 (Certificate Equivalence and Recomposition).
If two plan certificates are homotopy equivalent (Definition 1.20), univalence identifies them. This allows the meta‑safety layer to replace a verified plan with an equivalent one without re‑verification, facilitating modular updates.

Interface M→P (Meta‑Safety to Physical).
The USM outputs a meta‑certificate – a proof that the entire system (physical, somatic, reactive, cognitive) satisfies the global safety specification. This is a term of type

\mathsf{MetaCert} = \prod_{t:\mathbb{N}} \mathsf{SafeState}(t),

where \mathsf{SafeState}(t) asserts that the state at time t lies in the safe set \mathcal{C}. This meta‑certificate is constructed by composing the layer‑wise safety proofs.

