3. Formal Verification Chain

The architecture supports a chain of formal transformations that preserve safety properties. Each transformation is a morphism in an appropriate category.

Chain:

```
Physical Model (M_E4, g_S)
    ↓ [De Rham map I]
Somatic Bundle (SSM_E4)
    ↓ [Sheaf cohomology check → global section ŝ]
Somatic State Estimate (ŝ)
    ↓ [SCBF synthesis]
Safety-Preserving Control Law (safe envelope)
    ↓ [Dependent type checking]
Verified Plan (SafePlan type)
    ↓ [Homotopy equivalence / USM functor]
Meta-Safety Certificate (USM verification)
```

Theorem 3.1 (Chain Soundness).
If each arrow in the chain is a safety‑preserving morphism (in the sense that the output satisfies the safety property of the input under the appropriate interpretation), then the existence of a meta‑certificate implies that the physical system, when controlled according to the plan, remains within the safe set \mathcal{C} for all time.

Proof. By composition of the safety properties: the SCBF guarantees forward invariance, the plan respects the SCBF, the USM verifies the plan, and the meta‑certificate aggregates all proofs. Formalising this in type theory would involve constructing a term of type \mathsf{MetaCert} from the given certificates.

