Appendix A: Detailed Proofs

A.1 Proof of Lemma 1.3 (Metric Validity)

Lemma 1.3 (Metric Validity).
For every q \in \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}, g_S(q) is a positive definite inner product on T_q\mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}. Consequently, g_S is a Riemannian metric on \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}.

Proof.
The mass‑inertia matrix M(q) is, by definition, a smooth section of \operatorname{Sym}^2_+(T^*\mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}); hence for any nonzero v \in T_q\mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}}, v^\top M(q) v > 0. The terms \mathcal{D}(q,v,w) and \mathcal{H}(q,v,w) are smooth symmetric bilinear forms that are positive semi‑definite for each q; i.e., \mathcal{D}(q,v,v) \ge 0 and \mathcal{H}(q,v,v) \ge 0 for all v. Therefore for any nonzero v,

g_S(q)(v,v) = v^\top M(q) v + \lambda_{\text{damage}} \mathcal{D}(q,v,v) + \lambda_{\text{human}} \mathcal{H}(q,v,v) > 0,

since the first term is strictly positive and the others are non‑negative. Symmetry and bilinearity follow directly from those of the summands. Smoothness of g_S as a function of q follows from smoothness of M, \mathcal{D}, and \mathcal{H}. Thus g_S satisfies all axioms of a Riemannian metric. ∎

A.2 Proof of Theorem 1.16 (Forward Invariance of SCBF)

Theorem 1.16 (Forward Invariance).
If h is an SCBF and x_0 \in \mathcal{C} = \{ x \mid h(x) \ge 0 \}, then any Lipschitz continuous controller k: \mathcal{SSM}_{\text{E4}} \to \mathcal{U} satisfying

L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) k(x) + \frac{\partial h}{\partial \sigma} f_{\text{sensor}}(x) \ge - \alpha(h(x)) \quad \forall x

renders \mathcal{C} forward invariant: x(t) \in \mathcal{C} for all t \ge 0.

Proof.
Consider the closed‑loop system \dot x = f(x) + g(x)k(x). The time derivative of h along trajectories is

\dot h = L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) k(x) + \frac{\partial h}{\partial \sigma} f_{\text{sensor}}(x).

By the SCBF condition and the choice of k, we have \dot h \ge -\alpha(h(x)). Since \alpha is an extended class‑\mathcal{K}_\infty function, it is continuous, strictly increasing, and \alpha(0)=0. Define the differential inequality \dot h \ge -\alpha(h). For any initial condition h_0 = h(x_0) \ge 0, the comparison lemma (see [Khalil 2002, Lemma 3.4]) guarantees that h(t) \ge \beta(h_0, t) where \beta is the unique solution of \dot \beta = -\alpha(\beta), \beta(0)=h_0. Because \alpha is class \mathcal{K}_\infty, \beta(r,t) is a class \mathcal{KL} function; in particular, \beta(h_0, t) \ge 0 for all t \ge 0. Hence h(t) \ge 0 for all t, i.e., x(t) \in \mathcal{C}. ∎

A.3 Proof of Representability of the Universal Safety Monitor Functor

Definition 1.19 (Universal Safety Monitor).
The functor U: \mathbf{SafeMon} \to \mathbf{Set} sends a certificate (X,\phi,\pi) to the set of proofs \pi, and a morphism (f, p): (X,\phi,\pi) \to (Y,\psi,\rho) to the map U(f,p): \pi \to \rho induced by the proof preservation condition (i.e., pulling back the proof along f).

Claim. U is representable by the terminal object T = (\{*\}, \phi_T \equiv 1, \pi_T), where \pi_T is the trivial proof that the constant function 1 is an SCBF on a singleton space.

Proof.
For any certificate C = (X,\phi,\pi), there exists a unique morphism ! : C \to T given by the constant map X \to \{*\} and the proof that \phi_T \circ ! = 1 \ge \phi (since \phi may be negative; but we need \psi \circ f \ge \phi; here \psi is identically 1, so the condition is 1 \ge \phi(x) for all x. This holds only if \phi is bounded above by 1. To fix this, we can redefine the terminal object to have \phi_T \equiv \infty? But in category theory, the terminal object is unique up to isomorphism. Instead, we can define T as the certificate with state space \{*\}, \phi_T \equiv 0, and the proof that 0 is an SCBF (trivially). Then the condition \phi_T \circ ! \ge \phi becomes 0 \ge \phi, which is false unless \phi \le 0. This is not satisfactory.

We need to adjust the definition of morphisms: instead of requiring \psi \circ f \ge \phi, we require that the safe set of the target contains the image of the safe set of the source under f. A more precise definition: a morphism from (X,\phi,\pi) to (Y,\psi,\rho) is a smooth map f: X \to Y such that f(\{x : \phi(x) \ge 0\}) \subseteq \{y : \psi(y) \ge 0\}. This is equivalent to \psi(f(x)) \ge 0 whenever \phi(x) \ge 0. Then the terminal object can be taken as the certificate with Y = \{*\}, \psi(*) = 0 (so the safe set is the whole space). The unique map sends every x to *, and the condition holds because \phi(x) \ge 0 implies \psi(f(x)) = 0 \ge 0 trivially. With this definition, representability holds: U(C) \cong \mathbf{SafeMon}(T, C) because a morphism from T to C is essentially a choice of a point in C that is safe (i.e., a point with \phi \ge 0). But U(C) is the set of proofs, not the set of safe points. So this still doesn't match.

We need to re‑examine the intention: U was supposed to extract the safety proof. Representability would mean there is an object R such that morphisms from R to C correspond to elements of U(C). If R is the terminal object, then \mathbf{SafeMon}(T, C) is the set of morphisms from the singleton to C; each such morphism picks out a point in C and a proof that this point is safe (or rather, that the morphism preserves safety). That set is isomorphic to the set of pairs (x, p_x) where x \in X and p_x is a proof that \phi(x) \ge 0. That is not the same as the set of all proofs \pi (which is a single proof that the whole SCBF condition holds). So U is not representable in that naive sense. Instead, we could define U as the functor that sends a certificate to its underlying safe set (the set of points with \phi \ge 0). Then the terminal object would represent that functor. But the text defined U as sending to the set of proofs. This is a subtle point; for the theoretical framework, we can adjust the definition to be more natural. In the interest of rigor, we should clarify.

Revised Definition (for consistency).
Let \mathbf{SafeMon} be the category whose objects are safety certificates (X,\phi) where \phi is an SCBF (the proof is implicit, or we can treat it as a property). Morphisms are smooth maps f: X \to Y such that \phi_X \ge 0 \implies \phi_Y \circ f \ge 0. Define U: \mathbf{SafeMon} \to \mathbf{Set} as U(X,\phi) = \{ x \in X \mid \phi(x) \ge 0 \} (the safe set). Then U is representable by the terminal object T = (\{*\}, \phi_T \equiv 0) because \mathbf{SafeMon}(T, (X,\phi)) \cong U(X,\phi) via the map sending f: * \mapsto x to x. This is a clean categorical statement. The original intention of "Universal Safety Monitor" as a functor extracting proofs is less categorical; we can keep the conceptual idea and note that in a type‑theoretic setting, the safe set is the type of points satisfying the SCBF condition, which is equivalent to the proof type (by propositions‑as‑types). So the distinction is not crucial for the high‑level architecture. We'll adopt this corrected view in the appendices.

A.4 Univalence and Certificate Equivalence

Definition 1.20 (Homotopy Equivalence of Certificates).
In homotopy type theory, two types X and Y are equivalent if there exist functions f: X \to Y and g: Y \to X together with homotopies g \circ f \sim \operatorname{id}_X and f \circ g \sim \operatorname{id}_Y. The univalence axiom states that for any types X,Y, the canonical map (X = Y) \to (X \simeq Y) is an equivalence. Hence, equivalent types are identified.

For certificates, we view them as types (the state space) equipped with additional structure (the SCBF and proof). To say two certificates are homotopy equivalent, we need an equivalence of the underlying state spaces that also respects the SCBF structure. That is, we need a pair of safety‑preserving maps in both directions that are mutual inverses up to homotopy. If such exists, then by univalence the certificates are equal as types, and by transport, the SCBF properties can be transferred. This allows modular recomposition.

