Appendix B: Mathematical Background

B.1 Differential Geometry

Manifolds. A smooth manifold M of dimension n is a Hausdorff, second‑countable topological space locally homeomorphic to \mathbb{R}^n via smooth coordinate charts. The tangent space T_pM at a point p is the vector space of derivations of smooth functions at p. The tangent bundle TM is the disjoint union of tangent spaces, itself a smooth manifold.

Riemannian Metrics. A Riemannian metric g on M is a smooth section of \operatorname{Sym}^2_+(T^*M); i.e., for each p, g_p: T_pM \times T_pM \to \mathbb{R} is a positive definite symmetric bilinear form varying smoothly with p. The pair (M,g) is a Riemannian manifold. The length of a curve \gamma: [a,b] \to M is L(\gamma) = \int_a^b \sqrt{g(\dot\gamma(t),\dot\gamma(t))}\,dt. Geodesics are curves that locally minimize length; they satisfy the geodesic equation derived from the Levi‑Civita connection.

Lie Derivatives. For a vector field X and a function f, the Lie derivative L_X f = X(f) is the directional derivative. For a vector field Y, L_X Y = [X,Y] is the Lie bracket.

Fiber Bundles. A fiber bundle (E,\pi,M,F) consists of a total space E, base space M, projection \pi: E \to M a smooth submersion, and a typical fiber F such that locally E \cong U \times F. The tangent bundle and cotangent bundle are examples. A section is a smooth map s: M \to E with \pi \circ s = \operatorname{id}_M.

B.2 Information Geometry

Statistical Manifolds. A statistical manifold is a family of probability distributions parameterized by a smooth manifold. Formally, a statistical manifold is a triple (\Theta, \mathcal{X}, p) where \Theta is a smooth manifold, \mathcal{X} is a sample space, and p(x|\theta) is a probability density for each \theta, such that the mapping \theta \mapsto p(\cdot|\theta) is injective and smooth in an appropriate sense.

Fisher‑Rao Metric. For a parametric family \{p_\theta\}, the Fisher information matrix at \theta is

I_{ij}(\theta) = \mathbb{E}_{x\sim p_\theta}\left[ \frac{\partial \log p_\theta}{\partial \theta_i} \frac{\partial \log p_\theta}{\partial \theta_j} \right].

This defines a Riemannian metric on \Theta, the Fisher–Rao metric. It is invariant under reparameterization.

Exponential Families. Many common distributions (Gaussian, Poisson, etc.) form exponential families, where the Fisher metric has a convenient form.

B.3 Sheaf Theory

Presheaves and Sheaves. Let X be a topological space. A presheaf \mathcal{F} of sets (or vector spaces, etc.) assigns to each open set U \subseteq X a set \mathcal{F}(U) and to each inclusion V \subseteq U a restriction map \rho_{UV}: \mathcal{F}(U) \to \mathcal{F}(V) satisfying functoriality. A presheaf is a sheaf if for any open cover \{U_i\} of U and any family s_i \in \mathcal{F}(U_i) that agree on overlaps, there exists a unique s \in \mathcal{F}(U) restricting to each s_i.

Čech Cohomology. Given an open cover \mathcal{U} of X and a sheaf \mathcal{F}, the Čech cochain groups C^k(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{F}) are defined as products over (k+1)-fold intersections. The coboundary operator \delta yields a cochain complex, and the Čech cohomology groups H^k(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{F}) are its cohomology. For sufficiently fine covers, these coincide with sheaf cohomology.

Nerve. The nerve N(\mathcal{U}) of a cover is a simplicial complex with a vertex for each open set and a k-simplex for each nonempty (k+1)-fold intersection.

B.4 Control Barrier Functions

Definition. For a control system \dot x = f(x) + g(x)u with safe set \mathcal{C} = \{ x \mid h(x) \ge 0 \}, a function h is a control barrier function (CBF) if there exists an extended class‑\mathcal{K}_\infty function \alpha such that

\sup_{u \in \mathcal{U}} [L_f h(x) + L_g h(x) u] \ge -\alpha(h(x)) \quad \forall x.

If such a u exists, the set \mathcal{C} is forward invariant under any Lipschitz control satisfying the inequality.

Comparison Lemma. For a scalar differential inequality \dot y \le -\alpha(y) with \alpha class \mathcal{K}, the solution satisfies y(t) \le \beta(y_0,t) for some class \mathcal{KL} function \beta. The reverse inequality gives a lower bound.

B.5 Homotopy Type Theory

Identity Types. For any type A and elements a,b:A, the identity type a =_A b represents the proposition that a and b are equal. A term p: a = b is a proof of equality.

Homotopy Equivalence. A function f: A \to B is an equivalence if there exists g: B \to A and homotopies \eta: g \circ f \sim \operatorname{id}_A and \epsilon: f \circ g \sim \operatorname{id}_B. The type of equivalences is denoted A \simeq B.

Univalence Axiom. The univalence axiom states that the canonical map (A = B) \to (A \simeq B) is an equivalence. Hence, equivalent types can be identified.

Higher Inductive Types. These allow defining types with path constructors, useful for specifying spaces with nontrivial homotopy.

