Appendix C: E4‑Specific Parameterizations

C.1 Body Manifold Coordinates

The E4 platform has 28 rigid links, each with a configuration in SE(3). A convenient coordinate system for SE(3) is (p, R) where p \in \mathbb{R}^3 is position and R \in SO(3) is a rotation matrix. Alternatively, use exponential coordinates (v, \omega) for twists. The product manifold \prod_{i=1}^{28} SE(3)_i has dimension 28 \times 6 = 168. Flexible elements (e.g., soft coverings) add m coordinates; tool attachments add k coordinates. For concreteness, take m = 12 (describing deformation modes) and k = 6 (position and orientation of tool tip). Then \dim \mathcal{M}_{\text{E4}} = 168 + 12 + 6 = 186.

C.2 Explicit Safety Metric Terms

The bilinear form \mathcal{D}(q,v,w) penalizes motions that increase the risk of mechanical damage. It can be defined as

\mathcal{D}(q,v,w) = \sum_{j=1}^{N_{\text{joints}}} \kappa_j(q) \cdot (v_j w_j),

where v_j is the component of velocity along joint j, and \kappa_j(q) is a weighting that becomes large when joint j approaches its limit. For example,

\kappa_j(q) = \frac{1}{(\theta_j - \theta_j^{\min})^2} + \frac{1}{(\theta_j^{\max} - \theta_j)^2},

with \theta_j the joint angle. Similarly, \mathcal{H}(q,v,w) penalizes velocities toward humans:

\mathcal{H}(q,v,w) = \sum_{\text{human positions } h} \frac{1}{\|p_{\text{robot}}(q) - h\|^2} \cdot (v_{\text{radial}} w_{\text{radial}}),

where v_{\text{radial}} is the component of velocity directed toward the human. These terms are symmetric and positive semi‑definite.

C.3 Sensor Models

We list representative sensor models used in the E4 case study.

IMU (accelerometer + gyroscope).
Measurement model:

a_m = R(q)^\top (\ddot p - g) + b_a + n_a, \quad \omega_m = \omega + b_g + n_g,

where R(q) is orientation, g gravity, b biases (slowly varying), and n white noise with given covariance. The statistical manifold is parameterized by \theta = (\ddot p, \omega, b_a, b_g); the noise distributions define the Fisher metric.

Force‑sensitive resistor (FSR).
Output F_m = k F + n with known calibration k and additive Gaussian noise. The parameter is the true force F.

Joint encoder.
Measures joint angle \theta with quantization error uniformly distributed over [-q/2, q/2] where q is resolution. This is not a smooth family, but we can approximate by a Gaussian with variance q^2/12 for simplicity.

C.4 Sheaf Cover for E4 Sensors

The sensor cover \mathcal{U} is constructed as follows: each sensor has a domain of influence on the body (e.g., an FSR covers a small patch, an IMU covers the whole link). We take a cover by open sets U_\alpha each associated with a single sensor or a small group. The intersections correspond to regions covered by multiple sensors. For the E4 right arm, we might have:

· U_1: forearm skin (tactile sensors)
· U_2: forearm IMU
· U_3: wrist force/torque sensor
· U_4: elbow joint encoder
· etc.

The nerve is then a graph with edges where domains overlap. This structure supports sheaf‑based fusion.

C.5 Example SCBF Construction

Consider a simplified 1‑DOF arm with dynamics

\ddot \theta = u/M,

and a tactile sensor measuring contact force F. Let state x = (\theta, \dot\theta, F). Safe set: F \le F_{\max}. Define h(x) = F_{\max} - F. The SCBF condition becomes

\dot h = -\dot F = -\frac{\partial F}{\partial \theta} \dot\theta - \frac{\partial F}{\partial \dot\theta} u/M - \dots

Assuming F depends only on \theta via a spring model F = k(\theta - \theta_0), we get \dot F = k\dot\theta, so \dot h = -k\dot\theta. The SCBF condition requires

- k\dot\theta \ge -\alpha(h) \quad \Rightarrow \quad k\dot\theta \le \alpha(F_{\max}-F).

If \dot\theta is positive (moving into contact), we need \dot\theta \le \alpha(F_{\max}-F)/k. This can be enforced by limiting velocity.

